 [{'repository_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow', 'category': {'id': 32532274, 'node_id': 'MDE4OkRpc2N1c3Npb25DYXRlZ29yeTMyNTMyMjc0', 'repository_id': 9052236, 'emoji': ':pray:', 'name': 'Q&A', 'description': 'Ask the community for help', 'created_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'updated_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'slug': 'q-a', 'is_answerable': True}, 'answer_html_url': None, 'answer_chosen_at': None, 'answer_chosen_by': None, 'html_url': 'https://github.com/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1933', 'id': 3242657, 'node_id': 'MDEwOkRpc2N1c3Npb24zMjQyNjU3', 'number': 1933, 'title': 'How to use `publishDir` on a workflow output?', 'user': {'login': 'marcadella', 'id': 39333416, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjM5MzMzNDE2', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/39333416?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/marcadella', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/marcadella/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'user_view_type': 'public', 'site_admin': False}, 'labels': [{'id': 1402510710, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxNDAyNTEwNzEw', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/labels/lang/dsl2', 'name': 'lang/dsl2', 'color': 'E8448C', 'default': False, 'description': ''}], 'state': 'open', 'state_reason': None, 'locked': False, 'comments': 28, 'created_at': '2020-06-17T10:17:34Z', 'updated_at': '2023-04-06T16:52:16Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "It is possible to use `publishDir` in a process, but it doesn't seem possible to publish a workflow output channel (DSL2).\r\n\r\n", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1933/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1933/timeline'}, {'repository_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow', 'category': {'id': 32532274, 'node_id': 'MDE4OkRpc2N1c3Npb25DYXRlZ29yeTMyNTMyMjc0', 'repository_id': 9052236, 'emoji': ':pray:', 'name': 'Q&A', 'description': 'Ask the community for help', 'created_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'updated_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'slug': 'q-a', 'is_answerable': True}, 'answer_html_url': None, 'answer_chosen_at': None, 'answer_chosen_by': None, 'html_url': 'https://github.com/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1920', 'id': 3235600, 'node_id': 'MDEwOkRpc2N1c3Npb24zMjM1NjAw', 'number': 1920, 'title': 'Dealing with file globs in DSL2', 'user': {'login': 'maxbates', 'id': 3815620, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjM4MTU2MjA=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/3815620?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/maxbates', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/maxbates/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'user_view_type': 'public', 'site_admin': False}, 'labels': [], 'state': 'open', 'state_reason': None, 'locked': False, 'comments': 7, 'created_at': '2020-08-25T02:35:19Z', 'updated_at': '2022-06-28T17:51:51Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Hello! I\'m ramping up with DSL2, and hit a roadblock dealing with processes outputting a glob of files. I wonder if there is a better way to deal with these lists of files, but hopefully my code may help others.\r\n\r\nDSL2 modules are great, but the `publishDir` directive is unwieldy for processes imported across multiple workflows; I\'ve found it more tenable to explicitly define a tree of results at the end of my workflow. This requires mapping single files, files in directories, and array lists globbed files. I\'ve illustrated this below. \r\n\r\nI\'ve been confused by the changes to:\r\n- paths (which may be a single file, a glob or array list of files, or a directory - each with their own behavior)\r\n- files (`file()` appears to be supported, but the type is not recommended in process outputs in DSL2)\r\n- channels, which mostly seem to have fallen out of favor in DSL2 processes, and I haven\'t had much need for, except apparently in dealing with file globs, as below.\r\n\r\nUltimately, I\'m wondering if there is a better way to define `copyFilesFromGlob` - and think the docs would benefit from some further explanation or examples dealing with array lists of file paths:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnextflow.enable.dsl=2\r\n\r\nprocess create_files {\r\n\toutput:\r\n\t\tpath \'0.txt\', emit: "zero"\r\n\t\tpath \'*.txt\', emit: "files"\r\n\t\tpath \'dir\',   emit: "dir", type: "dir"\r\n\tscript:\r\n\t\t\'\'\'\r\n\t\techo \'zero\' > 0.txt\r\n\t\techo \'one\' > 1.txt\r\n\t\techo \'two\' > 2.txt\r\n\r\n\t\tmkdir -p dir\r\n\t\techo \'three\' > dir/3.txt\r\n\t\techo \'four\' > dir/4.txt\r\n\t\t\'\'\'\r\n}\r\n\r\ndef copyFilesFromGlob(files, target) {\r\n\t// files is an array of paths\r\n\t// appears to require an unintuitive subscribe() - e.g. each() does not work\r\n\tfiles.collect().flatten().subscribe { p -> \r\n\t\tf = file(p)\r\n\t\tif ( f.isFile() ) { \r\n\t\t\tf.copyTo("${target}/${f.getName()}")\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t}\r\n}\r\n\r\ndef copyDirectoryFiles(dir, target) {\r\n\tdir.eachFile { f -> \r\n \t\tif ( f.isFile() ) { \r\n \t\t\tf.copyTo("${target}/${f.getName()}")\r\n \t\t}\r\n \t}\r\n}\r\n\r\nworkflow {\r\n\tmain:\r\n\t\tcreate_files()\r\n\t\t(zero, files, dir) = create_files.out\r\n\r\n\t\t// creates /tmp/0.txt\r\n\t\t// [expected behavior]\r\n\t\tzero.copyTo("/tmp/0.txt")\r\n\r\n\t\t// fails\r\n\t\t// [expected, but docs not clear on what to do instead]\r\n\t\t// files.copyTo("/tmp")\r\n\r\n\t\t// fails\r\n\t\t// [unexpected, and not obvious to debug]\r\n\t\t// files.eachFile(f -> f.copyTo("/tmp/${f.getName()}"))\r\n\r\n\t\t// fails\r\n\t\t// [was surprising to me that files.eachFile() does not work]\r\n\t\t// copyDirectoryFiles(files, "/tmp")\r\n\r\n\t\t// creates /tmp/{1,2}.txt\r\n\t\t// [was not obvious to me in the docs how to achieve this behavior]\r\n\t\tcopyFilesFromGlob(files, "/tmp")\r\n\r\n\t\t// creates /tmp/{3,4}.txt\r\n\t\t// [expected]\r\n\t\tcopyDirectoryFiles(dir, "/tmp")\r\n\r\n\t\t// creates /tmp/dir/{3,4}.txt\r\n\t\t// [reasonable, but I had expected the files to copy to /tmp directly]\r\n\t\t// dir.copyTo("/tmp") \r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThanks for any pointers!', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1920/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1920/timeline'}, {'repository_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow', 'category': {'id': 32532274, 'node_id': 'MDE4OkRpc2N1c3Npb25DYXRlZ29yeTMyNTMyMjc0', 'repository_id': 9052236, 'emoji': ':pray:', 'name': 'Q&A', 'description': 'Ask the community for help', 'created_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'updated_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'slug': 'q-a', 'is_answerable': True}, 'answer_html_url': None, 'answer_chosen_at': None, 'answer_chosen_by': None, 'html_url': 'https://github.com/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1918', 'id': 3235594, 'node_id': 'MDEwOkRpc2N1c3Npb24zMjM1NTk0', 'number': 1918, 'title': 'Connecting subworkflows with DSL2', 'user': {'login': 'RenzoTale88', 'id': 23279528, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjIzMjc5NTI4', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/23279528?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/RenzoTale88', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RenzoTale88/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'user_view_type': 'public', 'site_admin': False}, 'labels': [], 'state': 'open', 'state_reason': None, 'locked': False, 'comments': 5, 'created_at': '2020-11-16T17:07:56Z', 'updated_at': '2022-06-15T02:22:06Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Hello,\r\nI\'ve been trying to learn how to migrate my workflows from nextflow DSL1 to DSL2, and I got a question concerning the use of sub-workflows. \r\nI\'m trying to migrate a small workflow that convert two genomes in 2bit format, and then generates the sizes files from those. Each of the two is a separate small workflow (creation of 2bit, followed by generation of the sizes), and the output of the first should be passed to the second.\r\nI\'ve created a structure of folders as follow:\r\n```\r\n./\r\n./modules/\r\n./modules/subworkflow\r\n./modules/processes\r\n./main.nf\r\n```\r\nWith the ```subworkflow``` contiaining the sub-workflow in .nf format and ```processes``` containing the processed that can be included by the different functions.\r\nI got a main workflow as follow:\r\n```\r\ninclude {TWOBIT; SIZES} from \'./modules/subworkflows/preprocess\' params(params)\r\nworkflow {\r\n        main:\r\n                TWOBIT()\r\n                TBS = TWOBIT.out.twoBitS\r\n                TBT = TWOBIT.out.twoBitT\r\n                SIZES(TBS, TBT)\r\n}\r\n```\r\nThis is calling these two sub-workflows, that look as follow:\r\n```\r\ninclude {make2bitS; make2bitT; makeSizeS; makeSizeT} from "../processes/preprocess" params(params)\r\n\r\nworkflow TWOBIT {\r\n    main:\r\n        // Make 2bit genomes\r\n        make2bitS()\r\n        make2bitT()\r\n    emit:\r\n        twoBitS = make2bitS.out.twoBsrc\r\n        twoBitT = make2bitT.out.twoBtgt\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nworkflow SIZES {\r\n    take:\r\n        2bitS\r\n        2bitT\r\n    main:\r\n        makeSizeS(2bitS)\r\n        makeSizeT(2bitT)\r\n    emit:\r\n        twoBitS = makeSizeS.out.sizesSrc\r\n        twoBitT = makeSizeT.out.sizesTgt\r\n\r\n}\r\n```\r\nThese in turn call the following functions:\r\n```\r\nprocess make2bitS {\r\n    tag "twoBit"\r\n    publishDir "$params.outdir/genome2bit"\r\n\r\n    output:\r\n    path "source.2bit", emit: twoBsrc\r\n\r\n    script:\r\n    """\r\n    faToTwoBit ${params.source} source.2bit\r\n    """\r\n}\r\n\r\nprocess makeSizeS {\r\n    tag "twoBit"\r\n    publishDir "$params.outdir/genome2bit"\r\n    input:\r\n    path src\r\n    output:\r\n    path "source.sizes", emit: sizesSrc\r\n    script:\r\n    """\r\n    twoBitInfo ${src} source.sizes\r\n    """\r\n}\r\nprocess make2bitT {\r\n    tag "twoBit"\r\n    publishDir "$params.outdir/genome2bit"\r\n    output:\r\n    path "target.2bit", emit: twoBtgt\r\n    script:\r\n    """\r\n    faToTwoBit ${params.target} target.2bit\r\n    """\r\n}\r\nprocess makeSizeT {\r\n    tag "twoBit"\r\n    publishDir "$params.outdir/genome2bit"\r\n    input:\r\n    path tgt\r\n    output:\r\n    path "target.sizes", emit: sizesTgt\r\n    script:\r\n    """\r\n    twoBitInfo ${tgt} target.sizes\r\n    """\r\n}\r\n``` \r\n\r\nHowever, when I run the pipeline, I get the following error:\r\n```\r\nModule compilation error\r\n- file : ./modules/subworkflows/preprocess.nf\r\n- cause: Workflow malformed parameter definition @ line 32, column 9.\r\n           2bitS\r\n           ^\r\n\r\nModule compilation error\r\n- file : ./modules/subworkflows/preprocess.nf\r\n- cause: Workflow malformed parameter definition @ line 33, column 9.\r\n           2bitT\r\n           ^\r\n\r\n2 errors\r\n```  \r\n\r\nSorry, it\'s probably a very simple mistake, but I\'m not sure to understand what it is it doesn\'t like. \r\n\r\nThank you in advance\r\nAndrea', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1918/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow/discussions/1918/timeline'}, {'repository_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/nextflow-io/nextflow', 'category': {'id': 32532274, 'node_id': 'MDE4OkRpc2N1c3Npb25DYXRlZ29yeTMyNTMyMjc0', 'repository_id': 9052236, 'emoji': ':pray:', 'name': 'Q&A', 'description': 'Ask the community for help', 'created_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'updated_at': '2021-01-31T15:04:22.000Z', 'slug': 'q-a', 'is_answerable': True}, 'answer_html_url': None, 'answer_chosen_at': None, 'answer_chosen_by': None, 'html_url': 'https://github.com/nextflow-io/nextflow/discuss